wjQbyz1F,Chapter 5 Reign Of quantity Guenon,markabelar,HTML,Wednesday 15th of November 2023 01:40:57 AM CDT,"CHaPter V

Time seems to be even further away than space from pure quantity. It is possible to speak of both temporal and spatial quantities, and both belong to the continuous quantity (since it is not necessary to dwell on the strange conception of Descartes, according to which time would be constituted by a series of discontinuous instants, which makes it necessary to suppose a constantly renewed ""creation"", without which the world would disappear at every moment in the intervals of this discontinuity)
column2: but a great distinction must be made between the two cases, since, as we have already indicated, while space can be measured directly, time can only be measured by reducing it, as it were, to space.

column1: What is really measured is never a duration, but the space covered during this duration in a certain movement whose law is known. By presenting this law as a relationship between time and space, we can, when we know the dimension of the covered space, deduce from it the dimension of the time used to cover it
column2: and whatever artifacts we employ, after all there is no other means than this to determine temporal quantities.1

column1: Another observation that also tends to the same conclusion is this: properly corporeal phenomena are the only ones that are located both in space and in time
column2: phenomena of a mental nature, those studied by

column1: psychology"" in the ordinary sense of the word, do not
have a spatial character, but instead also occur in time. If the nature of time allows it to be extended to the individual realm and hence

condition our own mental manifestations, then this nature must be even more qualitative than that of space. Since we are talking about mental phenomena, we will add that, insofar as they are on the side of what the essence represents in the individual, it is perfectly vain to look for quantitative elements in them
column2: although some go so far that they try to reduce them to quantity. What the ""psycho-physiologists"" determine quantitatively are not actually the mental phenomena properly speaking, as they imagine them, but only some of their bodily concomitants
column3: but there is nothing there that is in any way related to the very nature of the mind, nor therefore can serve to explain it in the least. The absurd idea of a quantitative psychology really represents the most accentuated degree of modern ""scientistic"" aberration!

column1: According to all this, if we can speak of a ""qualified"" space, we are even more justified to speak of a ""qualified"" time. By this we mean that there must be fewer quantitative determinations in time and more qualitative determinations than in space. ""Empty time"" has no more effective existence than ""empty space"", and in this respect everything that we have said about space could be repeated. There is no more time than space outside our world, and in it realized time always contains events, just as realized space always contains bodies.

In certain aspects there is a kind of symmetry between space and time, being able to speak of them in parallel. But this symmetry, which is not found with respect to the other conditions of bodily ex-istence, is perhaps due more to its qualitative side than to the quantitative side, as tends to be demonstrated by the difference that we have indicated between the determination of spatial and quantitative temporal magnitudes, and also by the absence, as regards time, of a quantitative science of the same type as geometry is for space.

On the other hand, in the qualitative order, symmetry is expressed in a particularly remarkable way by the correspondence that exists between spatial symbolism and temporal symbolism, and of which we have had occasion to give examples elsewhere
column2: as far as symbolism is concerned, in effect, it is evident that it is the consideration of quality that is essentially involved, and not that of quantity. It is evident that different periods of time are qualitatively differentiated by the events that occur in them, just as the portions of space are differentiated by the bodies they contain, and that we cannot in any way consider quantitatively similar durations, but filled by very different series of events
column3: it is even a common observation that the quantitative equality, in the mental appreciation of the duration, disappears completely before the qualitative difference.

column1: But it can be said that this difference is not inherent in duration itself, but only in what happens within it. We must therefore ask ourselves if there is not, on the contrary, in the qualitative determination of events, something that comes from time itself
column2: and, indeed, do we not at least implicitly recognize that this is so when we speak, for example, as we constantly do even in ordinary language, of the particular conditions of one or other period?

column1: This seems even more evident in the case of time than in that of space, although, as we have explained, the qualitative elements in the position of bodies are by no means negligible. And even if we wanted to get to the bottom of things, we could say that any body cannot be situated indifferently in any place, nor can any event occur indifferently at any time
column2: but here the symmetry is not perfect, because the position of a body in space is susceptible to variation due to the fact of movement, while that of an event in time is strictly determined and is properly ""unique"", so that the essential nature of events seems to be much more strictly related to time than that of bodies to space, which further confirms that time must itself have a more broadly qualitative character.

column1: The truth is that time is not something that develops in a uniform way and, therefore, its geometric representation by means of a straight line, as it is usually conceived by modern mathematicians, only gives a totally distorted idea of it, due to oversimplification. We shall see later that the tendency to oversimplify remains one of the characteristics of the modern mind and that, furthermore, it inevitably accompanies the tendency to reduce everything to quantity.
The true representation of time is provided by the traditional conception of cycles, a conception which, of course, is essentially that of a ""qualified"" time
column2: furthermore, insofar as it is a geometric representa-tion, either made graphically or simply expressed by the terminology used, it is evident that it is an application of spatial symbolism, and this should give rise to the idea that we can find in it a indication of a certain correlation between qualitative determinations of time and space.
for space, these determinations reside essentially in directions
column3: now the cyclical representation establishes precisely a correspondence between the phases of a temporal cycle and the directions of space. To convince ourselves of this, it is enough to consider an example taken from among the most simple and immediately accessible, that of the annual cycle, which plays, as is known, a very important role in traditional symbolism,2 in which the four seasons correspond to the four cardinal points?

column1: It is not necessary to develop here a more or less complete exposition of the doctrine of the cycles, although it is naturally implied in the very substance of the present study. In order to stay within the limits that we must impose on ourselves, we will content ourselves for the moment with making some observations more directly related to our subject as a whole, reserving the right to resort later to other considerations related to the same doctrine.

The first of these observations is that not only each phase of a temporal cycle, whatever it may be, has its own quality that influences the determination of events, but even the speed with which they develop is something that also depends on these phases and therefore is qualitative rather than quantitative in nature.

Thus, when we speak of this speed of events in time, by analogy with the speed of a body moving in space, we must make a certain transposition of this notion of speed, which can no longer be reduced to a quantitative expression such as the one related to the speed properly said in mechanics.

What we mean is that, according to the different phases of the cycle, the series of events that are comparable to each other do not occur in quantitatively equal durations. This is especially clear when it comes to the great cycles, both cosmic and human, and one of the most notable examples is the decreasing proportion of the respective durations of the four Yugas, which together make up the Manvantara.4

Precisely for this reason, events now unfold with a speed unparalleled in earlier times, a speed that is constantly accelerating and which will continue to do so until the end of the cycle. There is here a kind of progressive ""contraction"" of duration, the limit of which corresponds to the ""stopping point"" to which we have already alluded
column2: we will have to return to these considerations later and explain them in more detail.

column1: The second observation refers to the descending direction of the cycle, insofar as it is considered as the chronological expression of a process of manifestation that implies a progressive departure from the beginning
column2: but we have already talked about it often enough to do without dwelling on it again.

column1: We mention this point again mainly because, in relation to what we have just said, it gives rise to a rather interesting spatial analogy: the increase in the speed of events as we approach the end of the cycle can be compared to the acceleration that exists in the falling motion of heavy bodies
column2: the march of humanity today is truly similar to that of a mobile thrown down a slope, which moves all the faster the closer it is to the lowest point. Even if certain reactions in the opposite direction, insofar as they are possible, make things a little more complex, it is nevertheless a very exact picture of the cyclica movement taken in its generality.

column1: Finally, our third observation. When the downward march of the manifestation takes place, and consequently that of the cycle that is an expression of it, from the positive or essential pole of existence towards its negative or substantial pole, it follows that all things must take on an aspect that is less and less qualitative and more and more quantitative
column2: and that is why the last period of the cycle must particularly tend to assert itself as the ""reign of quantity"". Furthermore, when we say that this must occur in all things, we are not referring only to the way of seeing them from the human point of view, but also to a real change in the ""environment"" itself. Since each period in the history of humanity corresponds properly to a certain ""cosmic moment"" , there must necessarily be a constant correlation between the very state of the world, or what is called ""nature"" in the most common sense of the word, and more especially of the terrestrial environment as a whole, and that of humanity, whose existence is obviously conditioned by the latter.

column1: We can add that the total ignorance of these cosmic modifications is not the least cause of the misunderstanding of profane science with respect to everything that is outside certain limits. Born of the very special conditions of the present time, this science is evidently completely incapable of conceiving other conditions different from these, or even of admitting that they may exist, and thus the very point of view that defines it establishes ""barriers"" in the time that are as impossible to cross as it would be for a nearsighted to see clearly beyond a certain distance
column2: and indeed, the modern ""scien-tistic"" mentality is characterized in all respects by a true ""intellectual myopia"".

column1: We will develop this topic further later, in order to better understand what these changes in the environment may be, to which for now we can only refer to in a very general way. Perhaps it is understood that many things that today are considered ""fabulous"" were not so at all for the ancients, and that they may not even be so for those who have preserved, with the deposit of certain traditional knowledge, the notions that allow them to reconstitute the figure of a ""lost world"" , as well as foreseeing what the future world will be like. The past and the future correspond analogously, so that regardless of what ordinary mortals think, such predictions are not actually ""divinatory"" in the least, but are based entirely on what we have called the qualitative determinations of time.

We want to mention, with regard to the qualitative determinations of space and time and their correspondences, a testimony that is certainly not suspicious, since it is that of an ""official"" orientalist. Mr. Marcel Granet, who has dedicated a whole section of his work entitled La Pensée chinoise (Chinese thought) to these traditional notions. It goes without saying that the author only sees singularities in all this, which he tries to explain from a purely ""psychological"" and ""sociological"" point of view, but obviously we do not have to deal with this interpretation, which reflects modern prejudices in general and academics in particular, but it is the observation of the fact itself that is important to us here. In this sense, the book in question offers a striking image of the antithesis that a traditional civilization (and this would be equally true for any other than the Chinese) presents against the ""quanti-tative"" civilization of the modern West.
